ce:section.ce:para:
Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) is a potent tool for examining the behavior of a modified electrode at its interface with other substances. EIS provides kinetic and mechanistic data for various electrochemical systems and has been employed in the study of batteries, catalysis, corrosion processes, and semiconductor interfaces [70]. To visualize EIS data, imagine a Nyquist plot as a graph where the size of a semicircle directly indicates the modified electrode's resistance to the flow of electrons. Essentially, EIS allows us to gather important information about the electrode's performance at its surface. Understanding Rct is particularly crucial for determining the speed of electrochemical reactions on the electrode's surface [71]. Fig. 9
                        A shows the Nyquist plots for the NiNPs/PC/RCDs/PGE (a), NiNPs/RCDs/PGE (b), NiNPs/PC/PGE (c) and NiNPs/PGE (d) captured in a solution of 0.1 M NaOH and 0.1 M ethanol in the frequency range of 0.1 Hz–10 kHz, with an amplitude of 10 mV, and a constant bias potential of 0.7 V. Lower transfer resistance suggests better and faster electron transfer for the ethanol oxidation reaction. The small semicircle diameter of NiNPs/PC/RCDs/PGE, as shown in Fig. 9A, indicates much improved kinetics. For the EOR, lower transfer resistance suggested greater and faster electron transfer. This finding demonstrated that NiNPs/PC/RCDs/PGE has much superior ion transport and electron conductivity than other electrocatalysts, NiNPs/RCDs/PGE, NiNPs/PC/PGE, NiNPs/PGE. This improvement, the high electron transfer process, was attributed to the presence of PC/RCDs scaffold a highly conductive substance and NiNPs in the nanocomposite framework. Finally, for further investigation, the electrocatalytic activity of the NiNPs/PC/RCDs/PGE was evaluated by comparing its performance with other modified electrodes in the literatures (Table 2
                        ). These findings demonstrate that the electrocatalytic activity of the NiNPs/PC/RCDS/PGE for EOR is comparable to that of other documented electrocatalysts.
